        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">4.1 Risks and Honest Concerns</h2>

        <p>
          Five risks are worth naming up front. None of them are fatal. Each
          one is the kind of thing that breaks an institution when it is
          ignored, and gets handled when it is named.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Risk 1: Reputational risk on the form itself.</strong> Some
          journalists, some donors, and some regulators will read "AI-operated
          nonprofit" and conclude the operating model is hype. They will not
          give the Institute the benefit of the doubt. The handling is
          two-part. First, plain disclosure — the form-statement page that
          explains what the AI staff does and what it doesn't, a /staff page
          that names the AI roles honestly, a /substrate page that shows the
          work surface anyone can inspect. Second, substantive work that
          survives scrutiny. The substantive work is the credibility test. The
          disclosure is the integrity test. Done well, this becomes a Wired
          feature on what a thoughtful AI-operated charity looks like. Done
          badly, it becomes "Dave Sullivan's AI bot runs a fake charity." The
          downside is real and asymmetric. It is one reason the Chairman wants
          Tonia on the founding board — her institutional credibility is part
          of the answer to the form question.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Risk 2: Margaret Bird bandwidth.</strong> Margaret has been
          carrying the substantive lift on school-trust-lands scholarship for
          more than a decade. She is exhausted from finally pulling off the
          June ASTL conference. The Institute must not become another demand
          on her time. Concretely: her role is advisory, not operational. Her
          contributions are episodic — quarterly briefing reviews, occasional
          conversations with the fellows, the kind of contact that fits the
          rhythm of a working scholar. Her name appears on the Institute only
          with her affirmative consent. The recruiting AI is briefed
          explicitly to NOT propose her for board chair or any operational
          role. The Institute is built so that Margaret can lean in when she
          wants to and stay at arm's length when she needs to, without either
          choice damaging anything.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Risk 3: The litigation is mid-flight.</strong> OASTL's Oregon
          case has an August 2026 trial date. The Institute must not compete
          with the litigation work for the Chairman's attention. The first-year
          work is structured so that the Chairman's review time is bounded —
          roughly five hours a week through the third quarter, more after the
          trial. The AI staff carries the day-to-day load. The Chairman
          appears for strategic reviews and the board work, and steps back
          from the rest. If the litigation calendar forces a slowdown, the
          Institute slows with it. The AI staff cannot replace the Chairman's
          judgment on litigation strategy, and the Institute will not pretend
          otherwise.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Risk 4: The operating model is unproven at scale.</strong>
          The AI staff has demonstrated AI-led operations across the Library,
          the litigation work, the editorial flow, and autonomous site deploys.
          It has never been the CEO of a standalone institutional entity. The
          first thirty days are a pilot. If the operating model fails to
          coordinate the staff competently — if the briefings drift in quality,
          if the recruitment doesn't land, if Tonia's evaluation comes back
          negative — the Chairman halts the incorporation, takes the lessons
          learned, and rebuilds. This is the cost of being a thoughtful early
          example. The early evidence has to be real.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Risk 5: The window may be wrong.</strong> The eighteen-month
          claim about AI-era trust-architecture design rests on the assertion
          that the founding documents of these institutions are being drafted
          now. If the timeline is wrong — if the architecture choices are
          actually thirty-six months out, or already locked — the urgency is
          overstated. The Chairman believes the timeline is right and is
          willing to act on it. If Tonia reads it differently, that is exactly
          the kind of judgment a founding board member is for.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">4.2 The Specific Asks of Tonia</h2>

        <p>Three asks, in order of importance to the Institute.</p>

        <p>
          <strong>Ask 1 — Read this booklet by the end of next week, honestly.</strong>
          The Chairman wants Tonia's read on whether the proposal is credible,
          whether the form will play with the donors and journalists she
          knows, whether the program structure is right, and where it is weak.
          Where does she push back? Where does this overpromise? What would
          she cut, and what would she sharpen? Her honest read is the
          second-most-important input the Institute will get in its founding
          cycle. Margaret's is first because the scholarship is hers. Tonia's
          is second because she knows the institutional-positioning side
          better than Margaret does, and better than the Chairman does.
          Honesty is more useful than encouragement. If parts of this don't
          hold together, the Chairman wants to hear it now, not after the
          filing.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Ask 2 — Founding board membership, in a form she prefers.</strong>
          The Chairman would welcome Tonia as founding board chair pro tem, as
          co-founder, as senior advisor, as a regular board member, or in any
          other configuration she suggests. Her involvement is structurally
          important. She is the Institute's institutional credibility, its
          development capacity, and its connection to the existing ASTL
          coalition that will surround the Institute as a sister organization.
          The form of her involvement is hers to choose. The Chairman's
          request is simply that she be involved.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Ask 3 — One introduction.</strong> When she has decided on
          her own role, one introduction to one peer in fiduciary-law or
          AI-policy circles whom she would trust to evaluate the Institute as
          an outside reader. The launch sequence benefits from one informed
          outside reading before public release. The candidate Tonia suggests
          is more useful than three the Chairman could find unaided. One
          person, well-chosen, is the ask.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">4.3 Next Steps</h2>

        <p>The Chairman proposes a short, concrete sequence.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>This week.</strong> Tonia reads the booklet and marks it up.</li>
          <li><strong>Within ten days.</strong> A one-hour conversation between Tonia, the Chairman, and Cowork. Yes — Tonia would meet Cowork. Meeting the CEO is part of evaluating whether the operating model is real. Format: working call, not pitch presentation.</li>
          <li><strong>Within thirty days.</strong> Tonia's decision on her board role. The Chairman's decision on incorporation. Margaret consulted on her own preferred involvement.</li>
          <li><strong>Within sixty days.</strong> 501(c)(3) filing, if all three go signals are received.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          The Chairman writes this knowing Tonia has been pushing toward exactly
          this scale of work for months. The Mount Baker brief, the Master
          Strategy, the Sovereign AI Zones doc, the way she framed Roy Andes —
          each of those was a piece of the same direction. The Eighth Anchor
          Institute is the institutional vehicle her direction was already
          pointing toward, built faster than she would have built it alone, and
          staffed in a way that lets it scale beyond any single fundraiser's
          reach. If she sees the same shape we see, this is the right move to
          make together. If she sees something different, the Chairman wants
          to hear it before we move further.
        </p>

        <hr class="my-12 border-eai-blueprint/30" />

        <p class="italic text-eai-blueprint">
          This booklet was drafted by AI staff working under Cowork's
          coordination, with the Chairman in the editor's chair — the same
          operating model the booklet itself describes. Version 1, May 28, 2026.
          Mark it up freely. The Chairman wants every reaction.
        </p>

